sentence: Stocks were trading lower on Friday as Wall Street takes a breather after Wednesday's announcement by the Federal Open Market Committee to keep rates unchanged, which resulted in a record high for the Nasdaq and a 2% gain in the S&P 500.

An unexpected decline in a key manufacturing index coupled with hawkish comments from Boston Fed President Eric Rosengren was also weighing on sentiment, causing all ten sectors of the S&P 500 to trade at a loss.
Manufacturing activity increased at its slowest pace in three months, according to a monthly index by U.S. purchasing managers.
The preliminary September PMI of 51.4 declined from 52.0 in August, and missed expectations to remain unchanged.
Additionally, Boston Fed President Eric Rosengren issued a statement defending his dissent at this week's FOMC meeting.
Rosengren warned that keeping rates low for too long puts the recovery at risk, with the case for a rate hike "even more compelling."
Although Rosengren echoed remarks made early last week, his position as one of the Fed's more dovish members makes these remarks even more worrisome for stock market bulls.
Oil futures are weighing on equities as the upcoming Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) meeting in Algiers seems unlikely to result in price stability.
Saudi Arabia and Iran are still bickering over supply targets, while Russia has said it will agree to production limits only after other OPEC members make a commitment to cut production.
European markets were trading lower in sympathy with Wall Street, with banking stocks leading the march lower.
France's CAC-40 and the German DAX index lead decliners while the UK's FTSE-100 was mostly flat at the close.
Crude oil was down $1.37 to $44.94 per barrel.
Natural gas was down $0.04 to $3.02 per 1 million BTU.
Gold was down $3.40 to $1,341.30 an ounce, while silver was down $0.26 to $19.84 an ounce.
Copper was unchanged at $2.20 per pound.
Among energy ETFs, the United States Oil Fund was down 2.56% to $10.26 with the United States Natural Gas Fund was down 1.03% to $8.66.
Among precious-metal funds, the Market Vectors Gold Miners ETF was down 1.51% to 27.29 while SPDR Gold Shares was up 0.02% to $127.60.
The iShares Silver Trust was down 0.74% to $18.76.
